    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "> and got 0 feedback and review, help or encouragement, \r\n\r\nOn your original PR, I wrote https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/pull/22740#issuecomment-833360648\r\n\r\n> We're a bit sceptical about this, for a few reasons. For the state prefetcher, we think it's already bound by IO, and adding more threads that tries to resolve nodes would not improve the situation, it would only add more goroutines waiting for IO.\r\n\r\nYour follow up PR basically created goroutines like crazy to massively try to read from the backend. I had already said that we were sceptical about doing so. \r\n\r\n> even after I proved my case.\r\n\r\nOn a testcase, which runs in isolation, you were able to achieve higher speeds when you used \"unlimited\" number of goroutines to read. On a live blockchain, there are other things going on aswell, and we can't just have 1000 goroutines dedicated to hammering the disk. So in order for us to actually evaluate it, we would have to put it on on our benchmarking nodes, let it run for a week, and see the results. \r\n\r\nHowever, despite my already expressed scepticism about it, I would have done it on your PR, but apparently I was not fast enough for you.  \r\n\r\n>  and contributions are indeed unwelcome\r\n\r\nI'm one of the maintainers, and I've had _my own_ PRs sitting for months -- I think 1+ year has even happened in cases where my PRs touch places that are both consensus-critical _and_ are very complex. \r\n\r\nI'm sorry your experience wasn't what you had hoped for and that it ended on a sour note. ",
