    "body": "> If you had been this quick in trying to help me work things out as you have been trying to prove yourself right, we wouldn't have ended up here in the first place.\r\n\r\nWe don't owe you anything. Neither our time, nor any priority handling. I ran your code as a courtesy to @Dylan-Kerler, who asked nicely if the improvement was relevant or not.\r\n\r\nFor the record, benchmarks usually take a week to finish, unless the code is buggy or is an obvious deterioration in performance. When code reaches our benchmarkers, we don't expect them to blow up.\r\n\r\nI don't get why you're angry that we didn't put more time in it. Your code OOMs, and does so *fast*. This means you didn't even bother to try and run even a short sync cycle with it. If you couldn't even be bothered to sanity test your own code, turns out that the team was always right not to try and benchmark it. It just wasn't ready. It is not the Geth team's job to fix obvious issues. Yes, we can help iron out kinks or maybe discuss integration points, but first you need to prove it's worthwhile, which you didn't do.\r\n\r\nMy friendly suggestion for the future is to accept the working style of a team you're trying to contribute to, whether you like it or not. The world around you is not dumb and there are reasons processes work as they do. If you find them insufficient, try to understand why they are like that, and maybe afterwards suggest improvements. Trying to insult people and calling them things won't get your point across and will neither make you look good.\r\n\r\nLet's agree to part ways semi-amicably and stop escalating the situation. Wish you all the best in life.",
